Introduction¶

This dataset contains data on patient appointments. The features are patient details and the target is whether or not the patient will show up to their appointment.

The intent of this analysis is to find out the kind of relationship these features have with the target variable(if any). The result of this analysis is tentative and a further analysis can be done to build a classification Machine Learning model to help predict if a patient will show up in future.

Define Functions to visualize dataset¶

Defining functions to visualize data will help eliminate repitittion of code. The functions defined will be to plot

a. Histogram to view distribution of continuous variables
b. Pie Chart to view percentage of categorical variable in our sample
c. Detailed bar chart to show what proportions of attendance we have in relation to other categorical variables

a. Histogram to view distribution of continuous variables¶

In [30]:
# Define function

def cont_hist(df,col):
    # Select Column
    cont_var = df[col]

    # Get statistics
    minm = cont_var.min()
    maxm = cont_var.max()
    avg = cont_var.mean()

    print('Min {0}:{1}\nMax {0}:{2}\nAverage {0}:{3:.2f}\n'.format(col,minm,maxm,avg))

    # Plot Histogram
    cont_var.hist(figsize = (8,8))

    #Plot stat lines
    plt.axvline(x=minm, color='green', linestyle='dashed')
    plt.axvline(x=maxm, color='yellow', linestyle='dashed')
    plt.axvline(x=avg , color='red', linestyle='dashed')


    # Add title and axis labels
    plt.title('{} Distribution'.format(col))
    plt.xlabel('{}'.format(col))
    plt.ylabel('Number of Patients')

b. Pie Chart to view percentage of categorical variable in our sample¶

In [31]:
# Define function

# with labels
def var_pie_label(col,labels):
    #Plot pie chart
    ax = df[col].value_counts().plot(kind='pie', autopct='%.2f%%', title = 'Percentage of {}'.format(col), labels=labels, figsize = (8,8))
    # Remove column label from chart
    ax.yaxis.set_visible(False)
    plt.show()
    
# without labels
def var_pie(col):
    #Plot pie chart
    ax = df[col].value_counts().plot(kind='pie', autopct='%.2f%%', title = 'Percentage of {}'.format(col), figsize = (8,8))
    # Remove column label from chart
    ax.yaxis.set_visible(False)
    plt.show()

c. Detailed bar chart to show what proportions of attendance we have in relation to other categorical variables¶

In [32]:
# Define function

def var_proportion(data, labels, x_col):
        #calculate proportions
        counts = df.groupby(['No-show', x_col]).count()['ScheduledDay']
        totals = df.groupby('No-show').count()['ScheduledDay']
        attended = counts['Attended']/totals['Attended']
        missed = counts['Missed']/totals['Missed']
        
        #plot bar chart
        ind = np.arange(len(attended))  # the x locations for the groups
        width = 0.35 
        locations = ind + width / 2  # xtick locations
        
        attended_bars = plt.bar(ind, attended, width, color='g', alpha=.7, label='Attended')
        missed_bars = plt.bar(ind+width, missed, width, color='r', alpha=.7, label='Missed')
        
        
        plt.xticks(locations, labels)
        
        # title and labels
        plt.ylabel('Attendance Proportion')
        plt.xlabel('{}'.format(x_col))
        plt.title('Proportion of Attendance against {}'.format(x_col))
        
        # legend
        plt.legend(numpoints=1)
